			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				We essentially always had a two-party system from day one.  Sure occasionally a third part would show up here and there but basically we had two; be it Federalists or whigs or republicans or democrats.
<br />

<br />
Also, you have to look at the mindset of the everyday American.  Most voters do not know fully what the two parties stand for, they only grasp an issue or two that is important  for them; healthcare or education, or the environment, etc.  If you threw ten parties into the mix, sure there is an increased chance that one candidate out of the ten does closer represent what a particular voter stands for, the prospect of American voters actually realizing and understanding the party platform of ten would probably not be likely.
<br />

<br />
As much as I do agree with most of the Libertarian policies I do think it is a good idea to keep some of our military forces stationed overseas.  It is essentially like an isurance policy for us.  There is no way you could assume that at one point in the future some hostile action somewhere on the globe will not break out.  Since there is a chance of future danger the need for deployable forces stationed throughout the world is a significant advantage.
<br />
Not to mention those military units do training in those areas and they become familar with the geographical region.  That is something of value in itself.  Also the global economical impact of our military bases/forts all over the world is quite outstanding.  Apparantly some bases in Germany were going to close down and at first the Germans were happy.   Then they realized how much money they would lose and how it would devastate the local economy then they were not so thrilled about kicking the Americans out.  Ditto that with South Korea and Japan, chiefly.
<br />

<br />
Which brings me to my final point and the biggest issue I have with the Libertarian party; they are too idealistic.  Nearly everything they say is just too good to be true, and it is.  Maybe if we lived in a perfect world, the LP platform would be perfect; but, we don't.  I think that the LP is more like the Santa Claus of political parties.  Sure it is great, gives you that warm feeling deep down inside and makes everybody happy and joyfull; however, just like Santa it is not real.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
