				<div class="postbody">
				Libertarians are short-sighted, and their statement on military activities only reinforces that, at least to me.  They scare me, and I don't like to be scared.  
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Quote:
<br />
We call for the withdrawal of all American military personnel stationed abroad, including the countries of NATO Europe, Japan, the Philippines, Central America and South Korea. There is no current or foreseeable risk of any conventional military attack on the American people, particularly from long distances. We call for the withdrawal of the U.S. from commitments to engage in war on behalf of other governments and for abandonment of doctrines supporting military intervention such as the Monroe Doctrine.  </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It's this kind of "huddle in our shell and hope everything is okay out there" attitude that scares me.  Isolationism does not work.  We're the most powerful country in the world, and we have to take part in it's defense.  If you saw a man being attacked in the street, would you stand by and do nothing?
<br />

<br />
What do you do when Pakistan lobs a nuke at India?  Nothing?  Who do you think is preventing just that kind of thing from taking place right now?  The US and the US military presence is a stabalizing factor world-wide.  Remove it, and you basically set the stage for any country with an ambitious govornment (or no govornemt) to take from the weak.  Columbia would be over-run by the cartels.  Africa would fall into total chaos.  How long before another Milosivic comes to power somewhere in Eastern Europe?
<br />

<br />
If you fight a purely defensive war, you may win a lot of the battles, but you can't ever win the war.
<br />

<br />
How many of you played starcraft as the humans?  Against a skilled Zergling player...did the turtle defense ever work?  (Hint: The answer is no).  You can learn a lot from computer games.
<br />
 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">From reading this I suspect any part of the military that's not related to defense of the country on our own soil would get the axe. This is not necessarily a bad thing, and it needs to happen sometime,</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
Why?  The problem with a massive military cutback is that you drop hundereds of thousands, possibly millions, of people into the job market over a short period of time.  This would be a huge problem by itself, but the smaller our military gets, the more of a window we open for evil men to come to power.   
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Once upon a time we were not a two-party system. It just becaome that way by default a long time ago, and the republicrats took steps to make damn sure that no other party could be heard except for them. The current government can handle unlimited political parties, as none of its functions are party-dependent. Diversifying the base of the parties present would go a long way towards evening out the playing field for everyone. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Maybe you're right about that, I don't know.  But if you put to many voices in a room...you can't really hear any of them.  Since we're still the most powerful country in the world, the Republicrats must be doing something right....<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
