			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Idealism is what shold direct a party.
<br />

<br />
In the US, a very immature generation set a bad precedent in politics that has IMHO run it course and not yet been corrected.  The advent of TV as a means to spread communication had two effects in the 60s and 70s.  A unusually large amount of VERY young voters were captivated my charisma and made "issues" a very hot topic.  Hot like a hot potato.
<br />

<br />
The effect on the two parties was twofold.  New rules were set that made it so a viable candidate had to have charisma on camera.  The Other effect was that candidates could not have a platform of any real strength.  Sound bites and placebo stances on issues have ruled both parties for more than 30 years to cater to a public that was labeled as dull and shallow in the minds of the marketing men that had come to run campaigns.
<br />

<br />
In the 60s and 70s and into the 80s the Baby boomer geneeration was young, impressionable and thanks to a connstitutional amendment in 1972 (I think) were voting at age 18 not 21. This treatment of the public as "too stupid to think", has had an effect of turning voters off of the process within the parties.  Party membership represents a small percentage of the voting age population, and even the few that register actually make it to vote.
<br />

<br />
People do not relate with the parties because they do not take any real stances, not public ones at least.  They offer up the the public little Disneyland rides of a primary/caucus process with only warm fuzzy bumps and dips that seek to never offend.
<br />

<br />
The biggest upset and turn in direction of the american political landscape in the last 50 years was a small thrid party that got more than 10% of the vote in two presidential elections.
<br />

<br />
The Reform Party turned the politicians on their ear.  Whether you think Perot was a kook or a king doesnt matter.  What he did was come out and debate the major players and made them look like the microwave dinner category of  people that they are.  Most everyone that voted for Perot was there in his camp because he treated the public like thinking rational adults and took a firm stance on issues.
<br />

<br />
Even after he was crucified in the press, to make the showing that he did turned the other parties on their ear.  The budget was balanced (for a while, till it was clear the reform party wouldnt be an issue again) largely because of the influance that small voter rebellion caused.  I think that while Perot was a bit of a facist kook, he exemplifies the nations not only willingness but its actual want for politicians with stances.
<br />

<br />

<br />
###
<br />

<br />
At least when you vote libertarian you know what you are voting for.
<br />

<br />
When you are expousing a philosophy, you do not do so in a tepid and wishy washy fashion.  The Libertarian Party was formed on a core unified philosophy and it keeps it as an ideal to move towards.
<br />

<br />
A firm platform should not be a political liablity.  Seeking an ideal should not be either.  The only thing that makes it a liability is simply a matter of skewed perspective and it is a skew that happened in response to extraordinary circumstances 35 years ago.  That skew has been correcting itself in the people but the parties have not caught up.
<br />

<br />
People want to be able to trust that the representation they vote for is the one they get will get once the guy is in office. Politicians that make a career out of skimming profit out of public service would much rather have the ideals less defined and their options for fexibility open.  The schizm between the public and the two major parties is fractured by that very disparity in a type of market supply and demand.
<br />

<br />
The people want leaders and representation.  The politicians want influance and nonaccountability.  The politicians have a social contract to give the people what they want and of late that contract has not been well honored.  That is a setting for market shift and correction.  Demand will create new supply.
<br />

<br />
Voting for a any third party is a vote for accountability.  Libertarians IMHO take the now dead idealism that used to be the core of each major party and finds a common middle ground in reducing them to one common philosophy of responsibility and liberty.
<br />

<br />
Voting for a libertarian represents a Klaxon call to both parties to return to their roots and stop playing games and thinking they are out of reach of the voters supervision.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
